The required observational accuracy essentially dictates the volume that needs to be processed by the measurement device and the sampling resolution thus possible. In a very general form, the analysed air volume V is:V=αFτ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$V=\alpha F\tau$$\end{document}where α is the fraction of air that is analysed, F is the air flow rate at the inlet entry point [m3/s], and τ is the observation time interval [s].

A second relation connects the required observational accuracy and detection limit with the volume of air analysed. This can be expressed by the “shot noise” formalism, which describes the features of observations of rarely occurring events. In the case of airborne pollen or fungal spores, the rate event can be considered as a specific pollen particle being observed. From a statistical point of view, the detection of such particles can be modelled as a Poisson process, where the standard deviation is equal to the square root of the average particle concentration N. Employing the law of large numbers, the signal-to-noise ratio R is:R=NN=N.\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$R=\frac{N}{\sqrt{N}}=\sqrt{N}.$$\end{document}

From the above considerations, one can thus obtain the minimal flow rate Fmin if the maximum uncertainty γImax = 1/Rmin, required for a particular averaging period τ, and relevant concentration threshold Cthr are given by a user and the fraction α of the analysed air flow is a device internal feature:Fmin=1ατγmax2Cthr=Rmin2ατCthr\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${F}_{\mathrm{min}}=\frac{1}{\alpha \tau {\gamma }_{\mathrm{max}}^{2}{ C}_{\mathrm{thr}}}=\frac{{R}_{\mathrm{min}}^{2}}{\alpha \tau { C}_{\mathrm{thr}}}$$\end{document}

The recall is the fraction of the sampled particles that are correctly identified:Recall=TP/TP+FN\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{Recall}} = {\text{TP}}/{\text{TP}} + {\text{FN}}$$\end{document}

The precision is the proportion of correct classifications:Precision=TP/TP+FP\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{Precision}} = {\text{TP}}/{\text{TP}} + {\text{FP}}$$\end{document}

When assessing the quality of recognition, one can thus calculate an overall score which takes into account both the precision and recall, the F-score:F - score=2∗Recall∗Precision/(Recall+Precision)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$${\text{F - score}} = {2}*{\text{Recall}}*{\text{Precision/(Recall}} + {\text{Precision)}}$$\end{document}
